04569nam a22006375i 9780226555027DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017054497  a9780226555027  a(DE-B1597)521380  a(OCoLC)1046065762  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQC857.A92bC64 2018 4aQC857.A92bC64 2019 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a551.5092231 aCoen, Deborah R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClimate in Motion :bScience, Empire, and the Problem of Scale /cDeborah R. Coen. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b5 color plates, 45 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: Climate and Empire -- tPart 1. Unity in Diversity -- t1. The Habsburgs and the Collection of Nature -- t2. The Austrian Idea -- t3. The Imperial- Royal Scientist -- t4. The Dual Task -- tPart 2. The Scales of Empire -- t5. The Face of the Empire -- t6. The Invention of Climatography -- t7. The Power of Local Differences -- t8. Planetary Disturbances -- tPart 3. The Work of Scaling -- t9. The Forest- Climate Question -- t10. The Floral Archive -- t11. Landscapes of Desire -- tConclusion: After Empire -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday, predicting the impact of human activities on the earth’s climate hinges on tracking interactions among phenomena of radically different dimensions, from the molecular to the planetary. Climate in Motion shows that this multiscalar, multicausal framework emerged well before computers and satellites. Extending the history of modern climate science back into the nineteenth century, Deborah R. Coen uncovers its roots in the politics of empire-building in central and eastern Europe. She argues that essential elements of the modern understanding of climate arose as a means of thinking across scales in a state—the multinational Habsburg Monarchy, a patchwork of medieval kingdoms and modern laws—where such thinking was a political imperative. Led by Julius Hann in Vienna, Habsburg scientists were the first to investigate precisely how local winds and storms might be related to the general circulation of the earth’s atmosphere as a whole. Linking Habsburg climatology to the political and artistic experiments of late imperial Austria, Coen grounds the seemingly esoteric science of the atmosphere in the everyday experiences of an earlier era of globalization. Climate in Motion presents the history of modern climate science as a history of “scaling”—that is, the embodied work of moving between different frameworks for measuring the world. In this way, it offers a critical historical perspective on the concepts of scale that structure thinking about the climate crisis today and the range of possibilities for responding to it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aClimatologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aClimatologyxResearchzAustria. 0aSciencexPolitical aspectszAustria. 0aSciencezAustriaxHistoryy19th century. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aAustria.  aHabsburg.  aatmosphere.  aclimate.  aclimatology.  aempire.  aphysics.  ascale.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226555027423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226555027/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles